Decomposing the data¶

Using decomposition of the time series makes it easier to identify a changing mean or variation in the data quickly. The above plot clearly shows the upward trend of our data, the residual components, as well as its annual seasonality. These can be utilized to understand our time-series structure. The intuition behind time series decomposition is important, as many methods of forecasting build on this structured de concept

In [15]:
from pylab import rcParams
import statsmodels.api as sm
rcParams['figure.figsize'] = 11, 9


decomposition = sm.tsa.seasonal_decompose(times_series, model='additive', freq=52)
fig = decomposition.plot()
plt.show()
  • Thanks to the trend graph, we can see that the data is not constant over time which means that our process is probably not stationary

We will be dividing our data into test and train set

  • Train data: 80 percent
  • Test set: 20 percent
In [16]:
size = int(len(times_series) * 0.8)
train, test = times_series[0:size], times_series[size:len(times_series)]

stationarity¶

What is a stationarity process?

  • A process is stationary if its statistical properties such as mean, variance remain constant over time.

Method

  • To check the stationarity, we will be implementing the ADF (Augmented Dickey-Fuller) test.
In [17]:
result = adfuller(train)
In [18]:
print('ADF Statistic: %f' % result[0])
print('p-value: %f' % result[1])
print('Critical Values:')
for key, value in result[4].items():
	print('\t%s: %.3f' % (key, value))

ADF Statistic: -1.709684
p-value: 0.426130
Critical Values:
	1%: -3.434
	5%: -2.863
	10%: -2.568
  • H0: the process is not stationary
  • H1: the process is stationary

The p-value is higher than 0.05 (0.464520> 0.05) so we fail to reject the null hypothesis (H0), the data has a unit root and it is non stationary.

  • So we need to work on the stationarity of our process.

We will start by checking the lambda value.

In [19]:
from scipy.stats import boxcox

I could not generate the confidence inteval of lambda using python.So I used R and it had generated this output shown below.

The code that I used in R is :

  • library(MASS)
  • data = BOE_XUDLERD <- read_csv("BOE-XUDLERD.csv")
  • g <- lm(Value ~ Date, data=data)
  • boxcox(g, plotit = TRUE, lambda = seq(-4, 2, by = 0.1))

INTERPRETATION:

  • After fitting our model and generating the summary output of each possible arima model, I will be selecting the appropriate model.
  • the First criteria based on we will choose our model is the significance of the parameters: THE RULE : If the p-value, shown under the column labeled P>|t|, is less than the significance value of 0.05 then the parameter is significant.

IMA model (1,1) => the parameter θ is statistically significant ( the model is accepted)

ARIMA(1,1,1) model => the parameter Φ1 is not significant (The model is rejected)

ARIMA(1,1,0) model => the parameters are significant ( the model is accepted)

  • the Second criteria that based on we will choose our model is the AIC value (the Akaike Information Criterion):

    Among the accepted model, the model that had generated the lower AIC is model IMA(0,1,1)

Note: the AIC and the BIC generated are negative => Negative AIC and BIC indicates less information loss than a positive AIC and therefore a better model.

def forecast_accuracy(forecast, actual):
    mape = np.mean(np.abs(forecast - actual)/np.abs(actual))  # MAPE
    me = np.mean(forecast - actual)             # ME
    mae = np.mean(np.abs(forecast - actual))    # MAE
    mpe = np.mean((forecast - actual)/actual)   # MPE
    rmse = np.mean((forecast - actual)**2)**.5  # RMSE

    return({'mape':mape, 'me':me, 'mae': mae, 
            'mpe': mpe, 'rmse':rmse})

forecast_accuracy(fc, test.values)

Drawbacks of python¶

  • Through this project, I was able to learn more things about python.
  • One of the major drawbacks of python is that it doesn't have all the packages and enough statistical tools to make our analysis. Also, there are a several python codes for time series analysis in the internet. However, some of these codes are wrong and they are distorting our results.
  • I could not find the eacf function in the statsmodel.tsa package.
  • Python graphs are more visually pleasent.
  • Compared to python , R is much easier to work with. the major purpose of using R is for statistical analysis. That is why it is more trusted.

Overall, python does the job as R. However, we need to be more careful concerning the code used and the package used.

Packages verification¶

The statsmodel package : Most results have been verified with at least one other statistical package: R, Stata or SAS

the scipy.stats package boxcox:

This is the function used to ma ke the transformation

  • y = (x**lmbda - 1) / lmbda, for lmbda > 0
  • log(x), for lmbda = 0

For my data, I did not apply the log transformation I used the boxcox function just to generate the value of lambda I could not generate the confidence interval of lambda that is why I worked on R to check if 0 is included in the lambda interval. The results generated by R are the same as python.
